In computer science a string is any finite sequence of characters
                        (i.e., letters, numerals, symbols and punctuation marks).
An elementID is a special type of string returned by geometries and groups.
Number

A number is any real number, or an expression that evaluates to a real number
                        (e.g., -2, 3.14, 1/3).
Bool
In computer science, the bool data type has one of two possible Boolean values: true or false.
Array
In computer science, an array is a data structure that consists of a number of indexable elements.
This code sets the color of the cursor to blue:
let colors = ["blue", "green", "red"];
setColor(colors[0]);
box();
Data
Data can be of any valid JS datatype. This includes a strings, numbers, booleans, and objects among other datatypes.

children.value: The prism function makes a round 3D shape with three edges that meet at the top and bottom using the current cursor attributes. This function returns an

The resetCursor function resets the properties of the cursor to their defaults. This includes cursor attributes pertaining to Transformations and Animations.
The setColor function changes the color of the cursor. For general colors,
HTML color codes
can be used (e.g., "blue", "deeppink"), and for specific colors HEX colors can be used (e.g., "#00ffff"). The default cursor state is "red".
The getRandomColor function returns a random color and changes the color of the cursor. If passed an array, getRandomColor will choose randomly from the given colors.
The setPosition function changes the position of the cursor along all axes.  The default positions are x:0, y:0, z:0.
The setXPos function changes the x component of the position in the cursor. The default x position is 0.
The setYPos function changes the y component of the position in the cursor. To view negative coordinates, try turning off the floor in the scene settings. The default y position is 0.
The setZPos function changes the z component of the position in the cursor. The default z position is 0.
The increasePosition function increases the position of the cursor, or decreases the position using negative values. This function returns the position of the cursor after it is modified.

The increaseXPos function increases the x position of the cursor, or decreases the position using negative values. This function returns the x position after it is modified. The defualt increases the position by 1.

The increaseYPos function increases the y position of the cursor, or decreases the position using negative values. This function returns the y position after it is modified. The defualt increases the position by 1.

The increaseZPos function increases the z position of the cursor, or decreases the position using negative values. This function returns the z position after it is modified. The defualt increases the position by 1.

The setScale function changes the scale cursor component to the given ratios. Values greater than 1 make the object larger, and values between 0 and 1 make the object smaller. The default values are x:1, y:1, z:1.
The setXScale function changes the x component of the scale in the cursor. Values greater than 1 make the object larger, and values between 0 and 1 make the object smaller. The default x scale is 1.
The setYScale function changes the y component of the scale in the cursor. Values greater than 1 make the object larger, and values between 0 and 1 make the object smaller. The default y scale is 1.
The setZScale function changes the z component of the scale in the cursor. Values greater than 1 make the object larger, and values between 0 and 1 make the object smaller. The default z scale is 1.
The setRotation function changes the rotation in degrees around the x, y, and z axes. The default values are x:0, y:0, z:0.
The pitchX function changes the rotation in degrees around the x axis. The default value is 0.
The yawY function changes the rotation in degrees around the y axis. The default value is 0.
The rollZ function changes the rotation in degrees around the z axis. The default value is 0.
The setRadius function changes the radius of certain shapes. The shapes are: circle, cone, cylinder, dodecahedron, and torus. The default value is 1.

The setPhiLength function sets the phi length of the cursor in degrees. This changes the number of degrees shown of certain shapes. Interesting shapes can be achieved with values greater than 360. The default phi length is 360.
The makeDroppable function allows the element to be affected by physics and sets the element's mass.
The makeUnDroppable function prevents the given element from being affected by physics.
The makePushable function allows the object to be affected by physics and be pushed by clicking with the cursor.
The makeUnPushable function prevents the given element from being affected by physics or being pushed by the cursor.
The setCursorAttribute function allows the user to set a custom attribute and add it to the cursor.
The getCursorAttribute function allows the user to get a cursor attributes set by the setCursorAttribute function or by any other cursor setter.
The setLoop function sets the loop attribute in the cursor, turning infinite looping on and off. The default value is true.
The setDuration function sets the duration attribute of the cursor in milliseconds. The default value is 1000.
The setMagnitude function sets the magnitude attribute of the cursor in units or degrees. The default value is 1.
The spin function spins the given element around the y axis in degrees.
The yoyo function bounces the given element a number of units.
The sideToSide function shifts the element a number of units in the negative direction on the x axis.
The goUp function shifts the element "up", or a certain number of units in a positive direction on the y axis.
The goDown function shifts the element "down", or a certain number of units in a negative direction on the y axis.
The goRight function shifts the element "right", or a certain number of units in a positive direction on the x axis.
The goLeft function shifts the element "left", or a certain number of units in a negative direction on the x axis.
The goTowards function shifts the element "towards" the default camera view, or a certain number of units in a positive direction on the z axis.
The goAway function shifts the element "away" from the default camera view, or a certain number of units in a negative direction on the z axis.
The grow function scales the element by a [magnitude] multiplier in the x, y, z components.
The shrink function scales the element down by the inverse of the magnitude in the x, y, z components.
The fadeOut function shifts from transparency:1 (opaque) to transparency:magnitude. Magnitude should be between 0 and 1 inclusive.
The fadeIn function shifts from transparency:0 (invisible) to transparency:magnitude. Magnitude should be between 0 (exclusive) and 1 (inclusive).
The colorShift function shifts the element from its original color to the given color. All colors valid for setColor are applicable.
let
myGroup
= group
The group function creates an entity that can store other elements. This function does not draw anything.
myGroup
.add
The myGroup.add function adds an element to the group.
myGroup
.remove

The myGroup.remove function removes the given element from the group. The object will print with the cursor properties that it was made with, but will no longer be affected by modifications to the group.
myGroup
.setPosition
The myGroup.setPosition sets the position of the center of the group.
myGroup
.setScale
The myGroup.setScale function sets the scale of the group. Values greater than 1 make the entity larger, values between 0 and 1 will make the entity smaller.
myGroup
.setRotation
The myGroup.setRotation function sets the rotation of the group.
